description.narrative: Government duty bearers at levels are better able to deliver resourced, functional, comprehensive & coordinated child protection prevention and response services for children at risk or in need of care and protection, which contributes to Child Protection And Emergencies, Child Protection Systems, Justice For Children, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice (Covid), Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Girls and boys have access to and are better served by a national child protection system that prevents and responds to physical, sexual,and emotional violence, abuse, neglect, exploitation, harmful social practices and ensures access to adequate adult care across the lifecycle (young child, early adolescent, late adolescent)

description.narrative: With UNICEF support, child justice reform has been institutionalized through implementation of the National Child Justice Strategy (2020/21-2024/25) operationalizing child-friendly legal aid services, juvenile courts and diversion. Ninety-six per cent of social welfare officers are now trained in child protection in mainland and Zanzibar and provided child protection services to 6,542 children (Mainland) and 4,320 (Zanzibar). At district level, 90 mental health and psychosocial support teams are operational and have provided psychosocial support services to 195,257 children and adults affected by COVID-19. In the refugee camps, cumulatively 6,849, including newly identified 1,302 unaccompanied and separated children received child protection services. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:22/12/2021
